{"title_page": "List of Biman Bangladesh Airlines destinations", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n[[Biman Bangladesh Airlines]] was established in January 1972 as the Bangladesh national [[flag carrier]].<ref name=\"FI1979-1349\"/> Operations started on 4 February 1972, initially on a domestic basis and using [[DC-3]] aircraft, with services radiating from Dhaka to [[Chittagong]], [[Jessore (city)|Jessore]] and [[Sylhet]].<ref name=\"FI1973-446\"/> International operations started on 4 March the same year, covering the London\u2013[[Dhaka]] route on a charter basis under a sub-contract agreement with [[British Caledonian]].<ref name=\"FI1972-373\"/> From 1 January 1973 the same route, serving [[Gatwick Airport]], started being operated by [[Donaldson International Airways]] on Biman's behalf.<ref name=\"FI1973-446\"/> With a stopover in Bahrain, services to London in Biman's own right started on 19 June 1973,<ref name=\"FI1973-85\"/> initially with a [[Aircraft lease|leased]] [[Boeing 707]].<ref name=\"FI1973-6\"/> By {{start date|df=yes|1975|3}}, the domestic route network comprised [[Chittagong]], [[Comilla]], [[Cox's Bazar]], [[Ishwardi Upazila|Ishurdi]], [[Jessore (city)|Jessore]], [[Sylhet]] and [[Thakurgaon District|Thakurgaon]] and international services to [[Bangkok]], [[Calcutta]], Dubai, [[Kathmandu]], and London were also provided.<ref name=\"FI1975-475\" /> [[Frankfurt]] was first served in 1986.<ref name=\"Biman flies to Frankfurt again\" /> The [[Air carrier|carrier]]'s international network comprised 26 destinations in {{start date|df=yes|2005|3}},<ref name=\"Bangladesh Biman Plans Fleet Renewal\"/> but in 2006 services to some of them were discontinued, owing to financial problems of an outdated fleet and a shortage of modern planes, starting with New York City in {{MONTHNAME|8}} that year,<ref name=\"Biman Bangladesh Cuts Flights Because Of Cash Woes\"/> followed by some other destinations.<ref name=\"Biman Bangladesh To Receive Boeings From 2011\"/><ref name=\"2 more aircraft to board Biman fleet\" /> Frankfurt was resumed in late {{start date|2014|3}}.<ref name=\"New Dhaka-Frankfurt service\" /><ref name=\"Biman resumes Frankfurt flight after 8 years\" /> But the service proved economically unviable and the destination was again removed from the route network in {{MONTHNAME|10}} the same year<ref name=\"Biman flies to London 4 times a week\" /> and flights to Rome were suspended in {{end date|2015|4}}.<ref name=\"Biman plans to expand network\" /> \n\nThe airline had signed a deal with [[Boeing]] for ten new aircraft along with options for ten more in 2008.<ref name=\"Boeing starts $1.3b Biman plane supply\">{{cite news |last1=Ahmed |first1=Nizam |title=Boeing starts $1.3 bln Bangladesh plane supply 2011 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/bangladesh-airline-idUSSGE64701H20100508 |work=Reuters |date=8 May 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105155140/https://www.reuters.com/article/bangladesh-airline-idUSSGE64701H20100508 |archivedate=5 January 2016 |language=en}}</ref> After getting delivery of the new planes, Biman expanded its destinations gradually and increased in-flight amenities, especially onboard Internet and WiFi; mobile telephony; and live TV streams.<ref name=\"Internet in Biman\">{{cite news |last1=Moretaza |first1=Tareque |title=Biman offers phone, internet services in new aircraft |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/post/166753 |work=The Independent |date=17 September 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013014721/http://www.theindependentbd.com/post/166753 |archivedate=13 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Biman Internet Experience\">{{cite news |last1=Basher Anik |first1=Syed Samiul |title=How will Boeing 787 Dreamliner add a unique experience to Biman travel? |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/business/2018/06/28/how-will-boeing-787-dreamliner-add-a-unique-experience-to-biman-travel-2 |work=Dhaka Tribune |date=30 June 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013014531/https://www.dhakatribune.com/business/2018/06/28/how-will-boeing-787-dreamliner-add-a-unique-experience-to-biman-travel-2 |archivedate=13 October 2018 |language=English}}</ref> Biman Bangladesh Airlines is certified as safe to fly in Europe by the [[European Aviation Safety Agency]].<ref>[https://ec.europa.eu/transport/modes/air/safety/air-ban/doc/list_en.pdf \"List of airlines banned within the EU\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117224638/http://ec.europa.eu/transport/modes/air/safety/air-ban/doc/list_en.pdf |date=17 November 2012 }}, ''European Aviation Safety Agency'', 4 December 2012</ref><ref name=\"EU banned airlines\">{{cite web |title=Official Journal of the European Union |url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=OJ:L:2012:333:0007:0033:EN:PDF |website=European Aviation Safety Agency |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017225541/https://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=OJ:L:2012:333:0007:0033:EN:PDF |archivedate=17 October 2015 |language=en |date=4 December 2012}}</ref> In addition, Biman has also successfully passed the [[IATA Operational Safety Audit]] and since then, the airline has resumed flights to some of its previous destinations in Asia and Europe.<ref name=\"Bangladesh off the unsafe list\">{{cite news |first1=Shariful |last1=Islam |first2=Sayeda |last2=Akter |date=22 July 2012 |title=Bangladesh off the unsafe list |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-243084 |work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203060926/https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-243084 |archivedate=3 December 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"Biman gets int'l registration renewed\">{{cite news |title=Biman gets int'l registration renewed  |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-227362 |work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|date=23 March 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305061433/https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-227362 |archivedate=5 March 2017}}</ref> {{As of|2019|5}}, the airline serves 16 cities and destinations in 12 different countries across Asia and Europe. Biman Bangladesh Airlines restarted its direct flights to [[Indira Gandhi International Airport| Delhi]] in 2019 after a gap of six years.<ref name=\"DAC-DEL\">{{cite web| url=https://www.thedailystar.net/business/news/biman-resume-dhaka-delhi-flight-jet-air-bows-out-1732783| title= Biman to resume Dhaka-Delhi flight as Jet Air bows out| work=The Daily Star|accessdate=13 May 2019}}</ref> Shortly after, the airline also resumed its direct flights to [[Manchester]] which was last served until October 2012.<ref>https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/286708/biman-bangladesh-adds-madinah-manchester-service-in-w19/</ref>\n\n==List==\nFollowing is a list of destinations the carrier flies to according to its scheduled services, {{As of|2015|3|lc=y}}.<ref name=\"Network\" /><ref name=\"Schedules\">{{cite web|title= Flight Schedule|url= http://www.biman-airlines.com/bookings/flight_schedule.aspx|publisher= Biman Bangladesh Airlines|accessdate= 3 November 2014}}</ref> Terminated destinations are also listed together with both primary and secondary hubs of the airline.<ref name=\"Biman hubs\">{{cite news |title=Biman Signs Order for Three New Bombardier Q400 Aircraft |url=https://globenewswire.com/news-release/2018/09/10/1568564/0/en/Biman-Signs-Order-for-Three-New-Bombardier-Q400-Aircraft.html |work=Globe News Wire - News Room |date=10 September 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222105933/https://globenewswire.com/news-release/2018/09/10/1568564/0/en/Biman-Signs-Order-for-Three-New-Bombardier-Q400-Aircraft.html |archivedate=22 February 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n!Country\n!City\n!Airport\n!Notes\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Refs\n|-\n|Bahrain||[[Manama]]||[[Bahrain International Airport]]||{{terminated}}||align=center|<ref name=\"FI1998\"/>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"11\"|Bangladesh||[[Barisal]]||[[Barisal Airport]]||align=center| ||align=center|<ref name=\"Biman to resume flying on 5 domestic routes from Apr 6\">{{cite news |title=Biman to resume flying on 5 domestic routes from Apr 6 |newspaper=[[bdnews24.com]] |date={{Date|2015-2-19}} |url=http://bdnews24.com/business/2015/02/19/biman-to-resume-flying-on-5-domestic-routes-from-apr-6 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302221013/http://bdnews24.com/business/2015/02/19/biman-to-resume-flying-on-5-domestic-routes-from-apr-6 |archivedate=2 March 2015 |df=dmy }}&nbsp;</ref>\n|-\n|[[Chittagong]]||[[Shah Amanat International Airport]]||{{airline hub|'''Secondary Hub'''}}||align=center|<ref name=\"Biman hubs\" />\n|-\n|[[Comilla]]||[[Comilla Airport|Comilla STOLport]]{{#tag:ref|[[STOLport]] is an acronym for Short [[Takeoff]] and [[Landing]] Port|group=\"nb\"}}||{{terminated}}||align=center|<ref name=\"FI1979-1349\"/>\n|-\n|[[Cox's Bazar]]||[[Cox's Bazar Airport]]||align=center| ||align=center|<ref name=\"Biman to resume flying on 5 domestic routes from Apr 6\" />\n|-\n|[[Dhaka]]||[[Shahjalal International Airport]]||{{airline hub}}||align=center|<ref name=\"Biman hubs\" />\n|-\n|[[Ishwardi Upazila|Ishurdi]]||[[Ishwardi Airport|Ishwardi STOLport]]||{{terminated}}||align=center|<ref name=\"FI1979-1349\"/>\n|-\n|[[Jessore (city)|Jessore]]||[[Jessore Airport]]||align=center| ||align=center|<ref name=\"Biman to resume flying on 5 domestic routes from Apr 6\" />\n|-\n|[[Rajshahi]]||[[Shah Makhdum Airport]]||align=center| ||align=center|<ref name=\"Biman to resume flying on 5 domestic routes from Apr 6\" />\n|-\n|[[Saidpur, Rangpur Division|Saidpur]]||[[Saidpur Airport]]||align=center| ||align=center|<ref name=\"Biman to resume flying on 5 domestic routes from Apr 6\" />\n|-\n|[[Sylhet]]||[[Osmani International Airport]]||{{Airline hub|'''Secondary Hub'''}}||align=cente